{"content":"WEBVTT\n\n00:00.000 --> 00:27.500\nWhat if I told you there was nothing to be scared of?\n\n00:27.500 --> 00:37.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n00:37.500 --> 00:47.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n00:47.500 --> 01:15.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n01:15.500 --> 01:25.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n01:25.500 --> 01:35.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n01:35.500 --> 01:55.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n01:55.500 --> 02:15.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n02:15.500 --> 02:35.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n02:35.500 --> 03:03.500\nI'm going to show you what I'm going to show you.\n\n03:03.500 --> 03:11.500\nWe have this culture in TV, no matter how modern and progressive we get,\n\n03:11.500 --> 03:21.500\nno matter how sensitive and gentle we become, underneath it all, all of the men and women.\n\n03:21.500 --> 03:25.500\nI think we pride ourselves on an almost militaristic mindset.\n\n03:25.500 --> 03:35.500\nWe're doing something so important here that requires so much discipline and hierarchy and collaboration and intuitiveness.\n\n03:35.500 --> 03:45.500\nIt simultaneously dehumanizes the people you work with while making them the most important people in the world.\n\n03:45.500 --> 03:59.500\nI don't know if it's just my narcissism or if this is a common thing that people experience with grief,\n\n03:59.500 --> 04:05.500\nbut I just hear that someone is gone and then I'm immediately parsing it.\n\n04:05.500 --> 04:09.500\nWhat is wrong with me? What's wrong with me?\n\n04:09.500 --> 04:13.500\nWhat have I done? Why am I like this?\n\n04:13.500 --> 04:19.500\nWhy do I not understand that every single human being on earth,\n\n04:19.500 --> 04:25.500\nlike the ones you know, the ones you don't know, but especially the ones that you rely on every day,\n\n04:25.500 --> 04:33.500\nthe people that you just, in the truest sense of the phrase, take for granted?\n\n04:33.500 --> 04:41.500\nWhy is it so hard for us to go about our fucking day-to-day understanding that it's while very unlikely\n\n04:41.500 --> 04:46.500\nbut perfectly possible that someone will be gone tomorrow?\n\n04:46.500 --> 04:50.500\nAnd why can't we treat everybody and ourselves?\n\n04:50.500 --> 04:55.500\nI don't just mean like, oh, I was mean to this guy.\n\n04:55.500 --> 05:07.500\nWhat I was was completely just, I just didn't regard him as anything other than a load-bearing pillar of what we were doing,\n\n05:07.500 --> 05:16.500\nthat there would one day be some silly vacation to celebrate retirement or something, some opportunity,\n\n05:16.500 --> 05:26.500\nmaybe even the funeral of a person that was supposed to go on some schedule that I apparently think death works on,\n\n05:26.500 --> 05:32.500\nwhere we would finally sit down and interact as human beings.\n\n05:32.500 --> 05:40.500\nThat's my narcissism, parsing another person's death.\n\n05:40.500 --> 05:52.500\nIt's all about me, I guess, but I just feel like I'm made of straw tonight.\n\n05:52.500 --> 05:55.500\nI feel like if I move too quickly, my hand will fly off.\n\n05:55.500 --> 05:58.500\nI just feel like everything is so delicate.\n\n05:58.500 --> 06:00.500\nHow long did you know him for?\n\n06:00.500 --> 06:06.500\nWell, he's been there since the beginning, I mean since the moment that it became not a little pilot,\n\n06:06.500 --> 06:14.500\na little idea to the moment that it needed to start pulling up its big boy pants and being on the air, he was there.\n\n06:14.500 --> 06:24.500\nAnd he was unmistakably the reason why we're able to take something so childish where there's people having me sign\n\n06:24.500 --> 06:30.500\na corporate manufactured thing where the name of the character is Mr. Poopy Butthole.\n\n06:30.500 --> 06:42.500\nThe reason why you can be that stupid and childish and yet be so lucrative, compatible with mainstream society\n\n06:42.500 --> 06:47.500\nis because the guy is making the trains run on time.\n\n06:47.500 --> 06:52.500\nIt's coming to us from the Simpsons and the world of getting the job done.\n\n06:52.500 --> 07:00.500\nIf everybody was like me and Justin, you'd be watching two episodes of Rick and Morty every eight years.\n\n07:00.500 --> 07:03.500\nAnd it was out of the blue. I don't think I've ever met him.\n\n07:03.500 --> 07:04.500\nTotally out of the blue.\n\n07:04.500 --> 07:07.500\nAnd Levi said he was with him yesterday and everything was fine.\n\n07:07.500 --> 07:12.500\nThe crew went to the baseball game.\n\n07:12.500 --> 07:23.500\nThe upside is that he was surrounded by co-workers and they were all having a great time.\n\n07:23.500 --> 07:28.500\nHis wife and he just put a daughter in college and I just think it's such a rollercoaster ride.\n\n07:28.500 --> 07:32.500\nAll of these things, I guess that's the bargaining phase of...\n\n07:32.500 --> 07:33.500\nGreat for you.\n\n07:33.500 --> 07:37.500\nYou're kind of like, well, good thing it doesn't have a kid that's like six.\n\n07:37.500 --> 07:39.500\nAnd then I'm like, are you kidding me?\n\n07:39.500 --> 07:42.500\nA young adult has to spend the...\n\n07:42.500 --> 07:48.500\nThey're crossing a threshold into the rest of their life and you get this kneecap.\n\n07:48.500 --> 07:52.500\nThere's a little hatch here.\n\n07:52.500 --> 07:53.500\nI do two things.\n\n07:53.500 --> 07:55.500\nI go numb and I get mad.\n\n07:55.500 --> 08:01.500\nAnd I think that comes from upbringing and there's a hatch here where if I were to open it,\n\n08:01.500 --> 08:04.500\nwhich I won't do because it's bad podcasting,\n\n08:04.500 --> 08:10.500\nit does have to do with thinking about his wife who Rob and I was one of the first people that we worked with.\n\n08:10.500 --> 08:16.500\nShe was the casting director on Heat Vision and Jack and I'm just...\n\n08:16.500 --> 08:18.500\nThey were two lovely people.\n\n08:18.500 --> 08:21.500\nThey were just like great, wonderful people.\n\n08:21.500 --> 08:25.500\nIt's that thought because then that connects to the idea of my God.\n\n08:25.500 --> 08:27.500\nWhat if something happened to Cody?\n\n08:27.500 --> 08:29.500\nWhat if something happened to me?\n\n08:29.500 --> 08:35.500\nIt's just that I can't... I'm opening that hatch by saying I'm not opening that hatch.\n\n08:35.500 --> 08:38.500\nI can't go there.\n\n08:38.500 --> 08:50.500\nMy deepest sympathies and condolences to his family and I guess that's...\n\n08:50.500 --> 08:54.500\nI felt like I'd be remiss in not saying that this happened,\n\n08:54.500 --> 09:01.500\nbut at the same time, I could have said nothing.\n\n09:01.500 --> 09:07.500\nI don't consider it our job to stop the world and that doesn't do anybody any favors.\n\n09:07.500 --> 09:10.500\nI'm just very confused.\n\n09:10.500 --> 09:14.500\nI think there's one more thing that I would say about it,\n\n09:14.500 --> 09:24.500\nwhich is the continual frustration throughout the day of wanting someone to say something that finally makes sense,\n\n09:24.500 --> 09:29.500\nwhich I finally atoned with by around 3 p.m. today where I suddenly realized that,\n\n09:29.500 --> 09:44.500\nwait a minute, my big pet peeve with the deaths that we encounter is people making too much sense of them.\n\n09:44.500 --> 09:47.500\nI've talked about that here before.\n\n09:47.500 --> 09:53.500\nI was telling Dino today, Dino and I, no matter what we do until the day we finally die,\n\n09:53.500 --> 10:00.500\nand no matter how we die, if Dino or I walk under a piano and it falls on us,\n\n10:00.500 --> 10:02.500\npeople are going to make sense of that death.\n\n10:02.500 --> 10:07.500\nThey're going to go like, well, he had a problematic life and he was probably in the wrong place at the wrong time.\n\n10:07.500 --> 10:12.500\nThat piano had his name on it, the way and the choices he made.\n\n10:12.500 --> 10:20.500\nThat's my big pet peeve, in spite of the fact that as we all know, Dave Foley drinks 50 cups of coffee a day.\n\n10:20.500 --> 10:27.500\nThere's an instinct in us that no matter what happens to Dave, if he lives to 110 grade,\n\n10:27.500 --> 10:34.500\nif something terrible happens tomorrow, we want it to make sense because we are afraid of death.\n\n10:34.500 --> 10:36.500\nThis happened because of that.\n\n10:36.500 --> 10:37.500\nI got that figured out.\n\n10:37.500 --> 10:43.500\nI think the subtext of that is this really, really arrogant idea that all of us left\n\n10:43.500 --> 10:50.500\nbelonged to some club that made the right decisions and that is really offensive.\n\n10:50.500 --> 10:58.500\nAt least because it was so, it was like, I was getting angry about the nonsense of it.\n\n10:58.500 --> 10:59.500\nThis is a healthy man.\n\n10:59.500 --> 11:00.500\nHe played hockey.\n\n11:00.500 --> 11:03.500\nHe was ripped, man.\n\n11:03.500 --> 11:10.500\nHe was visceral.\n\n11:10.500 --> 11:17.500\nI'm like, someone tell me something and then I finally came around to, no, nobody tell me anything.\n\n11:17.500 --> 11:20.500\nPlease, dear God, give me a senseless death.\n\n11:20.500 --> 11:22.500\nGive me a confusing one.\n\n11:22.500 --> 11:28.500\nLet me go quickly and let people be puzzled by it.\n\n11:28.500 --> 11:35.500\nI think that may be the equivalent of leaving a little pencil splash in the pool and an Olympic dive.\n\n11:35.500 --> 11:43.500\nIf you know, just like no turbulence to the point where people are like, how'd that work?\n\n11:43.500 --> 11:48.500\nGod speed you, Mike.\n\n11:48.500 --> 11:59.500\nJust to make it about me one more time, I can't believe that guy left this world.\n\n11:59.500 --> 12:08.500\nHis story ends with Trump being president and me still working on a fucking draft of a script.\n\n12:08.500 --> 12:21.500\nI hope his last moments weren't fucking having to deal with my horrible bottleneck effect on production.\n\n12:21.500 --> 12:29.500\nWorking on this fucking draft and he's the guy that has to, he's got to be the hero.\n\n12:29.500 --> 12:34.500\nHe's got to absorb all that energy.\n\n12:34.500 --> 12:50.500\nI just hate myself for not turning that thing in, but it's stupid because getting to go to a baseball game is more important\n\n12:50.500 --> 12:55.500\nthan he wasn't going to get joy out of me finishing a draft.\n\n12:55.500 --> 12:58.500\nI talked enough about that.\n\n12:58.500 --> 13:06.500\nI had one item on my list, but it was kind of like, I think maybe Spencer, that's probably for a Spencer night.\n\n13:06.500 --> 13:10.500\nI don't want you to feel left out.\n\n13:10.500 --> 13:13.500\nYou're saving your best up for Spencer?\n\n13:13.500 --> 13:21.500\nI don't like this term hot swappable with hard drives.\n\n13:21.500 --> 13:23.500\nI just think it's a lie.\n\n13:23.500 --> 13:31.500\nYou get a drive, like a little thing that, oh, this reads these kind of cards or these disks and it's hot swappable.\n\n13:31.500 --> 13:36.500\nAnd the implication there is that, oh, so I can poke a little stick into my computer.\n\n13:36.500 --> 13:40.500\nI can write some stuff on it and I can pop it out, throw it in the other thing that I want to think.\n\n13:40.500 --> 13:43.500\nAnd the computer won't go, hey, what are you doing?\n\n13:43.500 --> 13:45.500\nOh, inject much.\n\n13:45.500 --> 13:48.500\nBut it does do that no matter what.\n\n13:48.500 --> 13:50.500\nThere is no such thing as a hot swappable drive.\n\n13:50.500 --> 13:51.500\nThank you.\n\n13:51.500 --> 13:55.500\nI'll be Spencer for you during this.\n\n13:55.500 --> 13:57.500\nI think he just did it.\n\n13:57.500 --> 13:58.500\nThat was it?\n\n13:58.500 --> 13:59.500\nYeah.\n\n13:59.500 --> 14:02.500\nI was just going to add, yeah, man.\n\n14:02.500 --> 14:04.500\nYeah, it's rough.\n\n14:04.500 --> 14:05.500\nYeah.\n\n14:05.500 --> 14:11.500\nYeah, what you really want to do is you get yourself a network card.\n\n14:11.500 --> 14:12.500\nOh, man.\n\n14:12.500 --> 14:13.500\nOh, man.\n\n14:13.500 --> 14:17.500\nYou got real blazing speeds there, real blazing speeds.\n\n14:17.500 --> 14:19.500\nWhere is he?\n\n14:19.500 --> 14:20.500\nWhere is Spencer?\n\n14:20.500 --> 14:22.500\nSpencer goes from that low.\n\n14:22.500 --> 14:23.500\nYeah, man.\n\n14:23.500 --> 14:24.500\nHe's down here.\n\n14:24.500 --> 14:26.500\nBut then he gets really up here.\n\n14:26.500 --> 14:28.500\nHe's got a lot of range.\n\n14:28.500 --> 14:30.500\nI don't know where Spencer is.\n\n14:30.500 --> 14:32.500\nAre we worried about him?\n\n14:32.500 --> 14:35.500\nWell, he's not here and you're doing reverse.\n\n14:35.500 --> 14:36.500\nHot swappable.\n\n14:36.500 --> 14:37.500\nYeah.\n\n14:37.500 --> 14:39.500\nMaybe Spencer's hot swappable.\n\n14:39.500 --> 14:41.500\nHe's just at a different podcast.\n\n14:41.500 --> 14:46.500\nI really hope this is not a long answer, but what is hot swapping?\n\n14:46.500 --> 14:49.500\nThat's where you poop on somebody's chest, right?\n\n14:49.500 --> 14:51.500\nWell, I would say a stint.\n\n14:51.500 --> 14:55.500\nI think in general, the concept is just the idea of being able to...\n\n14:55.500 --> 14:57.500\nSteve Levy in the booze, everybody.\n\n14:57.500 --> 14:59.500\nSteve Levy.\n\n14:59.500 --> 15:01.500\nHello, Steve.\n\n15:01.500 --> 15:03.500\nThat's an option.\n\n15:03.500 --> 15:04.500\nWhatever.\n\n15:04.500 --> 15:05.500\nSpencer took the night off.\n\n15:05.500 --> 15:06.500\nOh.\n\n15:14.500 --> 15:15.500\nWhat?\n\n15:15.500 --> 15:19.500\nPoor beleaguered saltmine worker, Rob Schrab.\n\n15:19.500 --> 15:23.500\nOh, you owe your soul to the company store, right?\n\n15:23.500 --> 15:25.500\nThis poor guy.\n\n15:25.500 --> 15:27.500\nThat's an option.\n\n15:27.500 --> 15:29.500\nWhat are you, Fred Flintstone?\n\n15:29.500 --> 15:31.500\nMr. Slate?\n\n15:31.500 --> 15:33.500\nI'm just whipping you.\n\n15:33.500 --> 15:36.500\nYeah, I got to make you come talk to Ed Newmire,\n\n15:36.500 --> 15:39.500\nthe author of the Robocop screenplay.\n\n15:39.500 --> 15:41.500\nThat was an awkward way to introduce our guest.\n\n15:41.500 --> 15:43.500\nLet's bring out Ed Newmire.\n\n15:51.500 --> 15:53.500\nHello, Ed.\n\n15:53.500 --> 15:55.500\nHello.\n\n15:59.500 --> 16:01.500\nDan, don't screw this up.\n\n16:01.500 --> 16:03.500\nThis is really important to me tonight.\n\n16:07.500 --> 16:09.500\nI'm sorry about those awful chairs.\n\n16:09.500 --> 16:13.500\nIntroduce or give him the, you know, the introduction\n\n16:13.500 --> 16:16.500\nthat a fellow of his stature deserves.\n\n16:16.500 --> 16:21.500\nI mean, my introduction of you would be one of my rambling things\n\n16:21.500 --> 16:23.500\nor Jeff would cut me off and say, please welcome Ed Newmire\n\n16:23.500 --> 16:25.500\nin the middle of me trying to introduce you\n\n16:25.500 --> 16:29.500\nbecause I'd be like, look, we've had some legends up here.\n\n16:29.500 --> 16:31.500\nI get nervous.\n\n16:31.500 --> 16:34.500\nI am a bad interviewer.\n\n16:34.500 --> 16:37.500\nBut there's a difference here where it's just like,\n\n16:37.500 --> 16:40.500\ngenuinely you are a hero to me.\n\n16:40.500 --> 16:45.500\nYou're a person that just exemplifies, like,\n\n16:45.500 --> 16:48.500\nnot only to me what we'll talk about,\n\n16:48.500 --> 16:50.500\nwhether you think this is true,\n\n16:50.500 --> 16:55.500\nbut it demonstrates the highest kind of, like,\n\n16:55.500 --> 17:01.500\ncoda of the craft of writing movies\n\n17:01.500 --> 17:05.500\nand also, like, demonstrates that that pays off,\n\n17:05.500 --> 17:08.500\nthat you pick your shots and whatever.\n\n17:08.500 --> 17:10.500\nBut let's get to know you a little bit\n\n17:10.500 --> 17:14.500\nbecause, God, I'm a bad interviewer.\n\n17:14.500 --> 17:19.500\nBut I think that we'll go through the early biography.\n\n17:19.500 --> 17:21.500\nLike, are you a Californian?\n\n17:21.500 --> 17:23.500\nWere you born here?\n\n17:23.500 --> 17:27.500\nI was actually born in Vienna, Austria by Chance\n\n17:27.500 --> 17:29.500\nand I grew up in the Marin County,\n\n17:29.500 --> 17:31.500\nSan Francisco Bay Area, Marin County.\n\n17:31.500 --> 17:33.500\nI grew up in San Samo.\n\n17:33.500 --> 17:35.500\nAnd you were a journalism major?\n\n17:35.500 --> 17:37.500\nYeah, my parents were both journalists\n\n17:37.500 --> 17:40.500\nand so that followed me through high school.\n\n17:40.500 --> 17:44.500\nI was the editor of my high school newspaper.\n\n17:44.500 --> 17:46.500\nBut I always wanted to do movies.\n\n17:46.500 --> 17:49.500\nWas there anything, too, because I was also a journalism major\n\n17:49.500 --> 17:52.500\nand my justification for it being from Wisconsin\n\n17:52.500 --> 17:56.500\nwas that I couldn't possibly make the leap\n\n17:56.500 --> 18:00.500\nto, well, I'm going to major in writing.\n\n18:00.500 --> 18:02.500\nI'm going to be a writer.\n\n18:02.500 --> 18:04.500\nI'm going to be creative for a living.\n\n18:04.500 --> 18:09.500\nI had to find a Midwestern-compatible version\n\n18:09.500 --> 18:11.500\nof being a person that sits at a typewriter\n\n18:11.500 --> 18:15.500\nthat also felt enough like welding to...\n\n18:15.500 --> 18:18.500\nWas there anything to that?\n\n18:18.500 --> 18:20.500\nIt was kind of the first time I ever had a little thing\n\n18:20.500 --> 18:22.500\nwhere you could do something.\n\n18:22.500 --> 18:25.500\nAnd I immediately started turning it into a place to do...\n\n18:25.500 --> 18:28.500\nI used to do violent satires, like my friend\n\n18:28.500 --> 18:30.500\nwho was the school president.\n\n18:30.500 --> 18:33.500\nWe shot him in front of the school.\n\n18:33.500 --> 18:36.500\nWe did Zapruder films and things like that.\n\n18:36.500 --> 18:40.500\nCertainly, propaganda is such a huge part\n\n18:40.500 --> 18:42.500\nof some of the most effective parts\n\n18:42.500 --> 18:44.500\nof the things you're most known for,\n\n18:44.500 --> 18:47.500\nlike the groupers, like both really interesting things\n\n18:47.500 --> 18:49.500\nto talk about.\n\n18:49.500 --> 18:53.500\nBut both of them have these Shakespearean heralds\n\n18:53.500 --> 18:55.500\nthat are the media.\n\n18:55.500 --> 18:57.500\nAnd so I imagine...\n\n18:57.500 --> 18:59.500\nI think I was always interested in that stuff.\n\n18:59.500 --> 19:01.500\nAnd I was literally all my...\n\n19:01.500 --> 19:04.500\nSome of my friends now were my people who were...\n\n19:04.500 --> 19:06.500\nLike Woodward and Bernstein were big guys.\n\n19:06.500 --> 19:09.500\nAnd so I know the guys who knew them and stuff like that.\n\n19:09.500 --> 19:11.500\nI know a lot of journalists and that kind of thing.\n\n19:11.500 --> 19:13.500\nAnd that was an exciting idea.\n\n19:13.500 --> 19:15.500\nThat here was the chorus.\n\n19:15.500 --> 19:17.500\nI don't know, it was an interesting device also.\n\n19:17.500 --> 19:19.500\nAnd it was cheap.\n\n19:19.500 --> 19:21.500\nYou could do a lot of things without spending any money.\n\n19:21.500 --> 19:23.500\nIt's the same as having a guy come out\n\n19:23.500 --> 19:26.500\nand explain the Montague's and the Capulets.\n\n19:26.500 --> 19:29.500\nThey're just like, well, here's what's going on.\n\n19:29.500 --> 19:33.500\nBut the more important thing is that unlike that guy,\n\n19:33.500 --> 19:36.500\nthe world as a character...\n\n19:36.500 --> 19:38.500\nDetroit is a character in Robocop.\n\n19:38.500 --> 19:41.500\nIt's so important to understand the relationship\n\n19:41.500 --> 19:44.500\nbetween people and media, what's going on in the world.\n\n19:44.500 --> 19:46.500\nAnd even though the whole story takes place\n\n19:46.500 --> 19:49.500\nin a really gritty, local part of this new earth,\n\n19:49.500 --> 19:54.500\nit's so effective to be able to zoom in\n\n19:54.500 --> 19:56.500\nfrom a global perspective.\n\n19:56.500 --> 19:58.500\nRight, and show other little parts of that world\n\n19:58.500 --> 20:00.500\nand imply a bigger world.\n\n20:00.500 --> 20:02.500\nAnd that was always there.\n\n20:02.500 --> 20:04.500\nAnd it was something that...\n\n20:04.500 --> 20:06.500\nI think Verhoeven had a big fight about that at one point\n\n20:06.500 --> 20:08.500\nbecause I always wanted it to be completely separate\n\n20:08.500 --> 20:10.500\nfrom the story, that it was different.\n\n20:10.500 --> 20:14.500\nOne time he said, well, maybe we'll be in a TV studio\n\n20:14.500 --> 20:16.500\nand you'll see the news and you'll...\n\n20:16.500 --> 20:18.500\nAnd I was like, I don't know why I was this way.\n\n20:18.500 --> 20:19.500\nI was 27 years old.\n\n20:19.500 --> 20:21.500\nI was like, no, that's terrible. You can't do that.\n\n20:21.500 --> 20:23.500\nWe had a huge fight about it.\n\n20:23.500 --> 20:24.500\nOh, really?\n\n20:24.500 --> 20:25.500\nYeah, and then he came around and he said,\n\n20:25.500 --> 20:26.500\nokay, all right, I get it.\n\n20:26.500 --> 20:28.500\nAnd then he said it was more...\n\n20:28.500 --> 20:30.500\nHe said, oh, that's actually more modern.\n\n20:30.500 --> 20:31.500\nThat's a really Brechtian idea.\n\n20:31.500 --> 20:35.500\nI don't think he said Brechtian, but it is a Brechtian idea.\n\n20:35.500 --> 20:37.500\nOkay, well, yeah, I'm kidding.\n\n20:37.500 --> 20:40.500\nSo because part of this is your story is interesting\n\n20:40.500 --> 20:42.500\nbecause Robocop, correct me if I'm wrong,\n\n20:42.500 --> 20:44.500\nthis is your first screen credit.\n\n20:44.500 --> 20:46.500\nIt's your first project.\n\n20:46.500 --> 20:47.500\nRight.\n\n20:47.500 --> 20:48.500\nI came to the business.\n\n20:48.500 --> 20:52.500\nI went to UCLA Film School and then my girlfriend\n\n20:52.500 --> 20:54.500\nbroke up with me and I couldn't finish UCLA's film school.\n\n20:54.500 --> 20:59.500\nBut I got a job on taxi and they paid me $175 a month\n\n20:59.500 --> 21:01.500\nor something to be a runner.\n\n21:01.500 --> 21:03.500\nAnd I did that for a little while.\n\n21:03.500 --> 21:06.500\nYou were a PA on taxi and which made us immediately go,\n\n21:06.500 --> 21:08.500\noh, was there an intersection between you and Sam Simon?\n\n21:08.500 --> 21:09.500\nAnd the answer's no, but...\n\n21:09.500 --> 21:11.500\nNo, no, but I did...\n\n21:11.500 --> 21:14.500\nI was the guy who used to sit outside the door\n\n21:14.500 --> 21:16.500\nand wait for the script pages.\n\n21:16.500 --> 21:19.500\nAnd I had to drive them to a place called Barber's Place\n\n21:19.500 --> 21:21.500\nand they typed them up and then I had to pick them up\n\n21:21.500 --> 21:22.500\nat six in the morning.\n\n21:22.500 --> 21:23.500\nAnd Barber's Place was what?\n\n21:23.500 --> 21:24.500\nIt was a typing place.\n\n21:24.500 --> 21:25.500\nIt was just where you typed your scripts up.\n\n21:25.500 --> 21:27.500\nThis was before there were computers.\n\n21:27.500 --> 21:28.500\nYeah.\n\n21:28.500 --> 21:30.500\nOh, yeah, I need myself.\n\n21:30.500 --> 21:31.500\nThey would type it.\n\n21:31.500 --> 21:32.500\nIt's not a copy place.\n\n21:32.500 --> 21:34.500\nIt was like they would just type them on.\n\n21:34.500 --> 21:36.500\nNo, they would literally...\n\n21:36.500 --> 21:38.500\nThere were a bunch of people who sat up, mostly women,\n\n21:38.500 --> 21:40.500\nwho sat up all night and re-typed the scripts.\n\n21:40.500 --> 21:42.500\nAnd then they were delivered to the...\n\n21:42.500 --> 21:45.500\nThey would take drafts with notes on them and stuff like that\n\n21:45.500 --> 21:47.500\nand just do a clean copy of them.\n\n21:47.500 --> 21:49.500\nRight, because there's no word processing.\n\n21:49.500 --> 21:51.500\nThey would give them to a guy and they would drive them\n\n21:51.500 --> 21:53.500\nin their little car and then go pick up a box of scripts.\n\n21:53.500 --> 21:55.500\nWe were talking about this afternoon,\n\n21:55.500 --> 21:59.500\nlike how there were so many roadblocks back then.\n\n21:59.500 --> 22:02.500\nAnd people still got stuff done.\n\n22:02.500 --> 22:04.500\nLike, where is it today?\n\n22:04.500 --> 22:06.500\nIt's like, oh, I can't connect with a Wi-Fi and print.\n\n22:06.500 --> 22:07.500\nFuck it.\n\n22:07.500 --> 22:08.500\nJust fuck it.\n\n22:08.500 --> 22:09.500\nYou know, it's like...\n\n22:09.500 --> 22:10.500\nI mean, including us, Jonathan.\n\n22:10.500 --> 22:12.500\nYeah, we were talking today about, you know,\n\n22:12.500 --> 22:15.500\nas people tend to in the loss of a colleague,\n\n22:15.500 --> 22:17.500\nwe're having drinks and we're suddenly going\n\n22:17.500 --> 22:18.500\nthrough our whole lives.\n\n22:18.500 --> 22:21.500\nAnd yeah, we were briefly marveling\n\n22:21.500 --> 22:24.500\nin how we had a radio show in Milwaukee\n\n22:24.500 --> 22:26.500\nand how we would get up at 5 a.m.,\n\n22:26.500 --> 22:29.500\ndrink two pots of coffee, write five scripts,\n\n22:29.500 --> 22:31.500\nget in a car, drive them down icy roads\n\n22:31.500 --> 22:34.500\nto a Kinko's because they had a printer\n\n22:34.500 --> 22:37.500\nand pay them the money that they wanted\n\n22:37.500 --> 22:40.500\nto print up these scripts and then drive.\n\n22:40.500 --> 22:42.500\nIt's like, yeah, I would never do that these days.\n\n22:42.500 --> 22:43.500\nYeah.\n\n22:43.500 --> 22:45.500\nAnyways, but you...\n\n22:45.500 --> 22:47.500\nAnd then right from that PA job,\n\n22:47.500 --> 22:55.500\nit says your Wikipedia page is so joyfully Spartan.\n\n22:55.500 --> 22:58.500\nYou're a proofreader at Paramount?\n\n22:58.500 --> 23:00.500\nNo, I was a scriptreader.\n\n23:00.500 --> 23:02.500\nI was a reader in the Story Analyst Guild.\n\n23:02.500 --> 23:04.500\nAnd they pay people.\n\n23:04.500 --> 23:05.500\nYou probably...\n\n23:05.500 --> 23:06.500\nDoing coverage?\n\n23:06.500 --> 23:07.500\nTo do coverage for executives.\n\n23:07.500 --> 23:09.500\nAnd you read everything that comes in\n\n23:09.500 --> 23:10.500\nand you do a report on it.\n\n23:10.500 --> 23:12.500\nYeah, they call a proofreader on your Wikipedia.\n\n23:12.500 --> 23:13.500\nYou're going to...\n\n23:13.500 --> 23:14.500\nYeah.\n\n23:14.500 --> 23:15.500\nSomeone's going to bring the hammer down.\n\n23:15.500 --> 23:17.500\nDo you remember any of the scripts that you read that went,\n\n23:17.500 --> 23:18.500\noh, this is great.\n\n23:18.500 --> 23:19.500\nSomebody...\n\n23:19.500 --> 23:20.500\nNo, no, I did.\n\n23:20.500 --> 23:21.500\nI remember reading Star Wars.\n\n23:21.500 --> 23:22.500\nStar Wars.\n\n23:22.500 --> 23:23.500\nI read War Games and I said,\n\n23:23.500 --> 23:24.500\nyou should make this movie.\n\n23:24.500 --> 23:26.500\nAnd they said, nobody wants to see a movie\n\n23:26.500 --> 23:27.500\nabout nuclear war.\n\n23:27.500 --> 23:36.500\nAnd then you said, but I can get you Daphne Coleman.\n\n23:36.500 --> 23:38.500\nAnd then I read a script which I really...\n\n23:38.500 --> 23:41.500\nI made my reputation at Columbia Pictures on these...\n\n23:41.500 --> 23:45.500\nI read a risky business and I wrote a coverage for it.\n\n23:45.500 --> 23:48.500\nIt was like 18 pages long, which is not what you want\n\n23:48.500 --> 23:50.500\nwhen you're an executive at the morning meeting.\n\n23:50.500 --> 23:51.500\nAnd I said, this is the greatest movie in the world.\n\n23:51.500 --> 23:52.500\nYou have to make it.\n\n23:52.500 --> 23:55.500\nAnd there was a memo came around and said,\n\n23:55.500 --> 23:58.500\nFrank Price, the chairman, saying that there would no longer be\n\n23:58.500 --> 24:00.500\nany coverage longer than two pages.\n\n24:00.500 --> 24:05.500\nAnd then when the movie came out,\n\n24:05.500 --> 24:07.500\nthey were interested in me suddenly.\n\n24:07.500 --> 24:10.500\nAnd when the movie came out, I bet somebody 100 bucks,\n\n24:10.500 --> 24:12.500\nthe vice president, that it was going to be a hit.\n\n24:12.500 --> 24:13.500\nAnd it was.\n\n24:13.500 --> 24:15.500\nAnd then suddenly they offered me a job.\n\n24:15.500 --> 24:19.500\nAnd for a moment, I was an executive who had his finger\n\n24:19.500 --> 24:21.500\non the pulse of youth.\n\n24:21.500 --> 24:24.500\nAnd that lasted for about a year at Universal.\n\n24:24.500 --> 24:26.500\nAnd I wasn't really suited for it.\n\n24:26.500 --> 24:30.500\nI read that you were offered to be the vice president at Universal.\n\n24:30.500 --> 24:32.500\nI was on a track.\n\n24:32.500 --> 24:34.500\nThey called them CEs now.\n\n24:34.500 --> 24:36.500\nI was a junior executive.\n\n24:36.500 --> 24:39.500\nAnd that's sort of how I learned all the business stuff,\n\n24:39.500 --> 24:40.500\nif you will.\n\n24:40.500 --> 24:41.500\nAnd I was under a VP.\n\n24:41.500 --> 24:44.500\nAnd yes, if I had stayed there, I would have been a VP,\n\n24:44.500 --> 24:46.500\nwhich I later was at another production company,\n\n24:46.500 --> 24:47.500\nMartin Rantsehoff.\n\n24:47.500 --> 24:50.500\nI was the VP of development and stuff like that.\n\n24:50.500 --> 24:52.500\nAnd this is where it gets really interesting.\n\n24:52.500 --> 24:56.500\nAnd this is where I start to kind of worship you\n\n24:56.500 --> 24:58.500\nin the story of your path.\n\n24:58.500 --> 25:04.500\nBecause in the underworld, where the werewolves of suits\n\n25:04.500 --> 25:07.500\nand the vampires of writers are in constant war,\n\n25:07.500 --> 25:09.500\nyou can root for one or the other.\n\n25:09.500 --> 25:12.500\nAnd there's all kinds of hybrids that are exciting and heroic.\n\n25:12.500 --> 25:14.500\nBut there is a war nonetheless.\n\n25:14.500 --> 25:18.500\nAnd so there is something really romantic about a guy\n\n25:18.500 --> 25:20.500\nthat does what you did.\n\n25:20.500 --> 25:24.500\nYou can just imagine the biopic tee-up of this moment,\n\n25:24.500 --> 25:29.500\nwhere you have this easier, you know, you're on this path.\n\n25:29.500 --> 25:32.500\nAnd then for whatever reason, you decide,\n\n25:32.500 --> 25:36.500\nno, I'd like to go behind door number two.\n\n25:36.500 --> 25:42.500\nI'm going to abandon this career of being liked,\n\n25:42.500 --> 25:46.500\nbeing on the side that calls the shots, makes the money.\n\n25:46.500 --> 25:49.500\nBecause I'm really passionate about this idea.\n\n25:49.500 --> 25:55.500\nI had called Robocop.\n\n25:55.500 --> 25:57.500\nIt's true.\n\n25:57.500 --> 26:00.500\nDuring this period, I thought, I'm really not this guy.\n\n26:00.500 --> 26:02.500\nI don't want to have...\n\n26:02.500 --> 26:05.500\nI wasn't good at returning 100 phone calls a day.\n\n26:05.500 --> 26:07.500\nAnd there were people who were.\n\n26:07.500 --> 26:09.500\nThere were people I really admired who really were good at that.\n\n26:09.500 --> 26:11.500\nSome of them are good writers, too.\n\n26:11.500 --> 26:15.500\nI mean, Mike Waldron, a shout out to him,\n\n26:15.500 --> 26:19.500\nhe was kind of an Ed Newmeyer at Star Burns,\n\n26:19.500 --> 26:22.500\nmy little studio where it was like,\n\n26:22.500 --> 26:24.500\nyou hire young people,\n\n26:24.500 --> 26:27.500\nand you make them do the stuff you're too busy to do.\n\n26:27.500 --> 26:30.500\nSome of it is reading other people's stuff, taking...\n\n26:30.500 --> 26:35.500\nIt's like, he's a very handsome kid from Georgia,\n\n26:35.500 --> 26:37.500\nand people like talking to him,\n\n26:37.500 --> 26:39.500\nand he doesn't mind talking on the phone,\n\n26:39.500 --> 26:40.500\nand I remember him saying to me,\n\n26:40.500 --> 26:43.500\njust so you remember, I did come out here to be a writer,\n\n26:43.500 --> 26:45.500\nand I was like, too bad, you're a daywalker.\n\n26:45.500 --> 26:48.500\nLike, Whistler's got more plans for you.\n\n26:48.500 --> 26:51.500\nBut I will return the favor to you\n\n26:51.500 --> 26:55.500\nif you do this shitty neurotypical stuff.\n\n26:55.500 --> 26:58.500\nI will help you as much as I can.\n\n26:58.500 --> 27:01.500\nAnd it amazes me that some people are just good at both,\n\n27:01.500 --> 27:04.500\nthat there are charming people who...\n\n27:04.500 --> 27:06.500\nYeah, they're good writers.\n\n27:06.500 --> 27:09.500\nThey're just cursed with this networking ability.\n\n27:09.500 --> 27:11.500\nYou know, I don't think I really did.\n\n27:11.500 --> 27:12.500\nI wasn't comfortable with that.\n\n27:12.500 --> 27:15.500\nI was never... I never felt cool enough for the job.\n\n27:15.500 --> 27:17.500\nAnd when I meet executives over time,\n\n27:17.500 --> 27:19.500\nthey all seem much cooler than I ever was.\n\n27:19.500 --> 27:23.500\nDo you buy into the dichotomy of the introvert versus the extrovert,\n\n27:23.500 --> 27:27.500\nwhere it's like the introvert is recharging their batteries\n\n27:27.500 --> 27:31.500\nwhile they're alone, while they're operating individually,\n\n27:31.500 --> 27:35.500\nand they don't mind interacting with other people,\n\n27:35.500 --> 27:36.500\nbut that's a discharge.\n\n27:36.500 --> 27:39.500\nAnd then there are some people who are actually receiving\n\n27:39.500 --> 27:42.500\nan energy charge from of all things\n\n27:42.500 --> 27:44.500\ninteracting with other people.\n\n27:44.500 --> 27:47.500\nAnd it gets them through having to play Minecraft,\n\n27:47.500 --> 27:48.500\nwhich blows my fucking mind.\n\n27:48.500 --> 27:49.500\nThey're just sitting there,\n\n27:49.500 --> 27:51.500\nso I hope the phone rings.\n\n27:51.500 --> 27:53.500\nThat's you.\n\n27:53.500 --> 27:56.500\nWhen you're sitting at home, you're like,\n\n27:56.500 --> 27:58.500\nGod damn it.\n\n27:58.500 --> 28:00.500\nI get ants in my pants.\n\n28:00.500 --> 28:02.500\nI gotta go out and be around the people.\n\n28:02.500 --> 28:06.500\nSo then you can recharge and get through those lonely nights\n\n28:06.500 --> 28:09.500\nbetween the sticks calling you\n\n28:09.500 --> 28:13.500\nand having you come out to a concert.\n\n28:13.500 --> 28:18.500\nI don't think we talked about my tour with sticks enough.\n\n28:18.500 --> 28:20.500\nI replaced Tommy's shot.\n\n28:20.500 --> 28:21.500\nNo, that's a...\n\n28:21.500 --> 28:22.500\nOkay, come on.\n\n28:22.500 --> 28:23.500\nYeah, I am an extrovert.\n\n28:23.500 --> 28:26.500\nI don't think I need other people to totally recharge,\n\n28:26.500 --> 28:27.500\nbut I do...\n\n28:27.500 --> 28:28.500\nI don't know.\n\n28:28.500 --> 28:31.500\nI think it's both ways.\n\n28:31.500 --> 28:32.500\nI need to be alone,\n\n28:32.500 --> 28:34.500\nbut I also need to be around people.\n\n28:34.500 --> 28:37.500\nAnd both of those are...\n\n28:37.500 --> 28:39.500\nRecharge and discharge in a way.\n\n28:39.500 --> 28:40.500\nWell, okay.\n\n28:40.500 --> 28:41.500\nAll right, so...\n\n28:41.500 --> 28:42.500\nCome on, man.\n\n28:42.500 --> 28:43.500\nYou figured out a way to be...\n\n28:43.500 --> 28:45.500\nYou don't have to choose one or the other.\n\n28:45.500 --> 28:47.500\nI'm not sure if I can answer this right,\n\n28:47.500 --> 28:49.500\nbut what I would say is...\n\n28:49.500 --> 28:50.500\nI always want to...\n\n28:50.500 --> 28:51.500\nWhen I was...\n\n28:51.500 --> 28:53.500\nMany years ago, when I wrote Robocop,\n\n28:53.500 --> 28:54.500\nand when it was successful,\n\n28:54.500 --> 28:56.500\nthere were times that I would entertain myself\n\n28:56.500 --> 28:58.500\nof thinking, well, I did this and I did that.\n\n28:58.500 --> 29:00.500\nI did that and I did that.\n\n29:00.500 --> 29:01.500\nLike thinking about...\n\n29:01.500 --> 29:03.500\nAnd then now, more and more,\n\n29:03.500 --> 29:05.500\nI think, well, no, I did that because Paul was there,\n\n29:05.500 --> 29:07.500\nand we talked about this.\n\n29:07.500 --> 29:09.500\nAnd we did this because John Davidson said,\n\n29:09.500 --> 29:11.500\nwell, you can have 25 cents to do that\n\n29:11.500 --> 29:12.500\nand some 10-foil.\n\n29:12.500 --> 29:14.500\nAnd there were a lot of people involved in that process\n\n29:14.500 --> 29:16.500\nthat made it what it was.\n\n29:16.500 --> 29:23.500\nAge sweetens the recognition of the myth...\n\n29:23.500 --> 29:25.500\nThat the auteur myth is an auteur.\n\n29:25.500 --> 29:27.500\nYou start to open up to...\n\n29:27.500 --> 29:29.500\nSo Verhoeven and I get together,\n\n29:29.500 --> 29:31.500\nand we've been getting together for 35 years,\n\n29:31.500 --> 29:33.500\nand we've done most of our work over breakfast.\n\n29:33.500 --> 29:35.500\nAnd we get together now still.\n\n29:35.500 --> 29:36.500\nWe just did recently.\n\n29:36.500 --> 29:37.500\nAnd the last time we got together,\n\n29:37.500 --> 29:39.500\nall we did was talk about what a great producer\n\n29:39.500 --> 29:40.500\nJohn Davidson was\n\n29:40.500 --> 29:42.500\nand how the movie never would have happened\n\n29:42.500 --> 29:44.500\nwithout John Davidson in a million different ways.\n\n29:44.500 --> 29:47.500\nNow, John and Paul didn't even speak during the movie.\n\n29:47.500 --> 29:50.500\nThey couldn't even talk to each other in the room.\n\n29:50.500 --> 29:53.500\nI was the middle child who would try to get the parents\n\n29:53.500 --> 29:54.500\nto come in and talk,\n\n29:54.500 --> 29:56.500\nand then they would run out after cursing at each other.\n\n29:56.500 --> 29:58.500\nBut now, they realize that it was...\n\n29:58.500 --> 30:00.500\nWell, I think they even did then.\n\n30:00.500 --> 30:02.500\nWhen you wrote it,\n\n30:02.500 --> 30:04.500\ndid you always, while you were writing this,\n\n30:04.500 --> 30:07.500\nbecause this is going to be called Robocop?\n\n30:07.500 --> 30:08.500\nI did.\n\n30:08.500 --> 30:11.500\nNo, no, it never ever happened to me since,\n\n30:11.500 --> 30:13.500\nbut it actually...\n\n30:13.500 --> 30:15.500\nI was working as a reader,\n\n30:15.500 --> 30:18.500\nand then Columbia Pictures was out,\n\n30:18.500 --> 30:19.500\nnot in Culver City,\n\n30:19.500 --> 30:22.500\nbut it was in Burbank on a lot called TBS then,\n\n30:22.500 --> 30:24.500\nwhich is now known as the Warner Brothers Lot.\n\n30:24.500 --> 30:26.500\nAnd I had an office right next to the...\n\n30:26.500 --> 30:27.500\nIt was a trailer office,\n\n30:27.500 --> 30:29.500\nand it was right next to one of the big backlots.\n\n30:29.500 --> 30:31.500\nAnd suddenly, they were making this giant picture,\n\n30:31.500 --> 30:33.500\nthis giant science fiction picture,\n\n30:33.500 --> 30:35.500\nwhich no one would tell you what it was.\n\n30:35.500 --> 30:36.500\nAnd I would get out of...\n\n30:36.500 --> 30:37.500\nI would leave my office,\n\n30:37.500 --> 30:39.500\nand I would go out onto the set.\n\n30:39.500 --> 30:41.500\nAnd what I really wanted to do in those days was make a movie.\n\n30:41.500 --> 30:43.500\nAnd there were so many people on this movie\n\n30:43.500 --> 30:45.500\nthat they didn't know who was working on it and who wasn't.\n\n30:45.500 --> 30:46.500\nThey were shooting all night,\n\n30:46.500 --> 30:48.500\nand so I would go and work on the art department\n\n30:48.500 --> 30:51.500\nand stay there until about three or four in the morning.\n\n30:51.500 --> 30:52.500\nAnd I said,\n\n30:52.500 --> 30:53.500\nso what's the first night?\n\n30:53.500 --> 30:54.500\nWhat's this movie about?\n\n30:54.500 --> 30:55.500\nAnd it's about a robot,\n\n30:55.500 --> 30:57.500\nand they pointed at a girl in a tutu\n\n30:57.500 --> 30:59.500\nand said, that's a robot.\n\n30:59.500 --> 31:01.500\nAnd it was Blade Runner.\n\n31:01.500 --> 31:03.500\nAnd then I watched them shoot someone Blade Runner.\n\n31:03.500 --> 31:05.500\nI was on that set.\n\n31:05.500 --> 31:06.500\nIt was extraordinary.\n\n31:06.500 --> 31:07.500\nI'd never seen anything like it.\n\n31:07.500 --> 31:10.500\nAnd then about three o'clock in the morning,\n\n31:10.500 --> 31:12.500\none night, I sort of had this idea\n\n31:12.500 --> 31:15.500\nof what I thought a robot should look like on that street.\n\n31:15.500 --> 31:17.500\nAnd it was looking...\n\n31:17.500 --> 31:19.500\nIt was a robot that looked a little like Robocop.\n\n31:19.500 --> 31:21.500\nAnd it was next to that blue car.\n\n31:21.500 --> 31:23.500\nThey call it the spinner.\n\n31:23.500 --> 31:26.500\nAnd suddenly, the title just...\n\n31:26.500 --> 31:29.500\ncame into my mind, like Robocop.\n\n31:29.500 --> 31:30.500\nBoom.\n\n31:30.500 --> 31:31.500\nAnd it was really weird.\n\n31:31.500 --> 31:33.500\nAnd I think it's the power of location.\n\n31:33.500 --> 31:34.500\nI truly do.\n\n31:34.500 --> 31:35.500\nIf you are on a...\n\n31:35.500 --> 31:36.500\nIt's very...\n\n31:36.500 --> 31:37.500\nAt least for me, location and architecture\n\n31:37.500 --> 31:38.500\nand things like that,\n\n31:38.500 --> 31:40.500\nare very creative ideas come to me in that.\n\n31:40.500 --> 31:43.500\nAnd I think that was such a supercharged set\n\n31:43.500 --> 31:45.500\nfor a young man to be on, like...\n\n31:45.500 --> 31:48.500\nNow, looking backwards through...\n\n31:48.500 --> 31:51.500\nSo that kid who's having that moment is like,\n\n31:51.500 --> 31:53.500\nokay, I think I'm gonna write this movie.\n\n31:53.500 --> 31:54.500\nIt's gonna be called Robocop.\n\n31:54.500 --> 31:55.500\nI don't want him to be in a tutu.\n\n31:55.500 --> 31:56.500\nI want him to...\n\n31:56.500 --> 31:58.500\nWhatever happened to the...\n\n31:58.500 --> 32:01.500\nIt's a very Schrabby sounding thing.\n\n32:01.500 --> 32:02.500\nThis is Rob Schrab.\n\n32:02.500 --> 32:03.500\nI'm Rob Schrab.\n\n32:03.500 --> 32:08.500\nTo be like, come on, it's a robot.\n\n32:08.500 --> 32:09.500\nHello.\n\n32:09.500 --> 32:12.500\nIf you knock on it, your hand should hurt.\n\n32:18.500 --> 32:20.500\nAnd after like 30 years, it becomes a...\n\n32:20.500 --> 32:23.500\nThat was the original poster.\n\n32:23.500 --> 32:27.500\nThe poster for you kids was Robocop climbing out of the car\n\n32:27.500 --> 32:29.500\nand the poster said,\n\n32:29.500 --> 32:33.500\npart man, part machine, all cop.\n\n32:33.500 --> 32:35.500\nAnd I remember being 15 and I was like,\n\n32:35.500 --> 32:37.500\nhere's the thing is that until you see that movie,\n\n32:37.500 --> 32:38.500\nuntil you see a frame of it,\n\n32:38.500 --> 32:41.500\nI mean, you're a wash in a world of like,\n\n32:41.500 --> 32:44.500\noh, Spielberg came out with six pieces of crap,\n\n32:44.500 --> 32:46.500\none of them will stick and write history.\n\n32:46.500 --> 32:47.500\nAnd you're very...\n\n32:47.500 --> 32:49.500\nYou're jaded even back then.\n\n32:49.500 --> 32:50.500\nAnd you have permission to be jaded.\n\n32:50.500 --> 32:52.500\nAnd I saw that poster and I was like,\n\n32:52.500 --> 32:53.500\nthis is...\n\n32:53.500 --> 32:55.500\nThis misses the mark.\n\n32:55.500 --> 32:56.500\nThis is silly.\n\n32:56.500 --> 32:57.500\nWhat do they mean Robocop?\n\n32:57.500 --> 32:59.500\nLike Schrab said backstage.\n\n32:59.500 --> 33:01.500\nIt sounds like a kid's movie.\n\n33:01.500 --> 33:04.500\nNow, this is the difficult part of the question.\n\n33:04.500 --> 33:07.500\nSo this kid who's visualizing this,\n\n33:07.500 --> 33:11.500\nat that point, where are you at tonally?\n\n33:11.500 --> 33:14.500\nAre you thinking to yourself...\n\n33:14.500 --> 33:19.500\nThat part of the point of it is that it's going to be\n\n33:19.500 --> 33:23.500\na disarming like hypodermic for some seriously\n\n33:23.500 --> 33:26.500\nlike potent kind of edge?\n\n33:26.500 --> 33:29.500\nOr are you simply at that time going like,\n\n33:29.500 --> 33:31.500\ngee whiz robots are swell?\n\n33:31.500 --> 33:32.500\nYeah, no, no.\n\n33:32.500 --> 33:35.500\nI think the answer is there were two levels going on.\n\n33:35.500 --> 33:38.500\nThere was this has to be a movie for eight year olds or whatever.\n\n33:38.500 --> 33:41.500\nAnd this has to be a movie for people who were thinking.\n\n33:41.500 --> 33:43.500\nAnd it can be both of those things at the same time.\n\n33:43.500 --> 33:45.500\nI don't think I immediately thought that.\n\n33:45.500 --> 33:48.500\nWhat I thought was I want to make a movie about business\n\n33:48.500 --> 33:51.500\nand how the corporate world is a dangerous world.\n\n33:51.500 --> 33:54.500\nI wanted to see businessmen killing each other.\n\n33:54.500 --> 33:56.500\nAnd that that was because...\n\n33:56.500 --> 33:57.500\nYou weren't thinking that.\n\n33:57.500 --> 33:58.500\nI was thinking that.\n\n33:58.500 --> 33:59.500\nOh, okay, sorry.\n\n33:59.500 --> 34:01.500\nThat's what I was really thinking about the time\n\n34:01.500 --> 34:02.500\nwas before robots even was,\n\n34:02.500 --> 34:04.500\noh, I want to do a world about business\n\n34:04.500 --> 34:06.500\nwhere executives actually kill each other.\n\n34:06.500 --> 34:09.500\nAnd so that title, the idea that would always be called that title,\n\n34:09.500 --> 34:12.500\nand the fact that that title sounds a little silly.\n\n34:12.500 --> 34:15.500\nFrom the very beginning, that was all as designed.\n\n34:15.500 --> 34:19.500\nYou were thinking, it's like naming your movie\n\n34:19.500 --> 34:23.500\nlike Mr. Stretchy or something.\n\n34:23.500 --> 34:25.500\nIt's kind of like supposed to sound childish.\n\n34:25.500 --> 34:27.500\nI used to say it's good.\n\n34:27.500 --> 34:29.500\nI used to say, oh, that's really stupid.\n\n34:29.500 --> 34:30.500\nMeaning that's really good.\n\n34:30.500 --> 34:31.500\nThat's really wonderful.\n\n34:31.500 --> 34:32.500\nFucking love it.\n\n34:32.500 --> 34:33.500\nFucking love it.\n\n34:33.500 --> 34:34.500\nFucking love it.\n\n34:34.500 --> 34:37.500\nThat was my big go-to was, oh, that's kind of stupid.\n\n34:37.500 --> 34:38.500\nLet's do that.\n\n34:38.500 --> 34:41.500\nMonster House.\n\n34:42.500 --> 34:44.500\nThe house is a monster.\n\n34:44.500 --> 34:48.500\nKung Fu Panda.\n\n34:48.500 --> 34:50.500\nBut it did imply another part of this world\n\n34:50.500 --> 34:52.500\nthat also had to support all of that.\n\n34:52.500 --> 34:55.500\nAnd the more difficult part of it was to convince people\n\n34:55.500 --> 34:57.500\nthat it could be funny.\n\n34:57.500 --> 34:59.500\nEverybody wanted it to be straight.\n\n34:59.500 --> 35:02.500\nAnd it was, I always knew it would have impact.\n\n35:02.500 --> 35:04.500\nBut I really had this theory,\n\n35:04.500 --> 35:06.500\nmaybe someone else had had it,\n\n35:06.500 --> 35:08.500\nbut as a young man trying to figure out how to write a screenplay,\n\n35:08.500 --> 35:12.500\nI had this idea that if you had a really, really violent scene\n\n35:12.500 --> 35:15.500\nthat was shocking, and then you told a joke,\n\n35:15.500 --> 35:17.500\neven a bad one afterwards, it would be much funnier.\n\n35:17.500 --> 35:20.500\nAnd that was one of the things that was invested throughout writing.\n\n35:20.500 --> 35:23.500\nWhen I think of the movies, we all love this movie to pieces.\n\n35:23.500 --> 35:27.500\nWe always talk about what are the few, like,\n\n35:27.500 --> 35:30.500\nhandful of just perfect movies that you wouldn't take anything out of\n\n35:30.500 --> 35:31.500\nor add anything to.\n\n35:31.500 --> 35:35.500\nAnd Robocop is for us definitely one of those movies.\n\n35:35.500 --> 35:37.500\nI think it's very sad.\n\n35:37.500 --> 35:40.500\nIt's an incredibly sad film.\n\n35:40.500 --> 35:43.500\nAt the core, it's a really depressing story.\n\n35:43.500 --> 35:45.500\nAnd it's really about how he's...\n\n35:45.500 --> 35:49.500\nI remember I was, I think what you do when you do something the first time\n\n35:49.500 --> 35:52.500\nor what I often hear other people talking about\n\n35:52.500 --> 35:55.500\nis you're kind of making up your own rules for how you do something\n\n35:55.500 --> 35:57.500\nand you have to figure it out yourself.\n\n35:57.500 --> 36:00.500\nAnd that was really, that was me trying to figure out something.\n\n36:00.500 --> 36:01.500\nHow does three acts work?\n\n36:01.500 --> 36:03.500\nHere's the beginning, middle, and the end.\n\n36:03.500 --> 36:04.500\nI mean, boy, you've lost.\n\n36:04.500 --> 36:07.500\nYou wielded the fucking...\n\n36:07.500 --> 36:09.500\nIt's really intimidating\n\n36:09.500 --> 36:10.500\nbecause I actually...\n\n36:10.500 --> 36:12.500\nGod damn it.\n\n36:12.500 --> 36:14.500\nI still haven't...\n\n36:14.500 --> 36:17.500\nI still can't write a decent three act story.\n\n36:17.500 --> 36:25.500\nAnd part of my training was trying to get Sid Field's stuff to work for me\n\n36:25.500 --> 36:30.500\nby deconstructing Robocop and Die Hard really specifically.\n\n36:30.500 --> 36:34.500\nAnd even more so than Die Hard,\n\n36:34.500 --> 36:40.500\nwhich I really fetishize a great deal on this stage.\n\n36:40.500 --> 36:43.500\nRobocop is just...\n\n36:43.500 --> 36:48.500\nIt's uncanny the structural integrity of that story.\n\n36:48.500 --> 36:51.500\nCan I ask a bunch of questions here, please?\n\n36:51.500 --> 36:54.500\nOkay, so...\n\n36:54.500 --> 36:56.500\nWhat's it like to kiss a girl?\n\n36:56.500 --> 36:58.500\nShut up. Just shut up.\n\n36:58.500 --> 37:01.500\nJust shut your mouth.\n\n37:01.500 --> 37:02.500\nDon't listen to him.\n\n37:02.500 --> 37:03.500\nIt wasn't me.\n\n37:03.500 --> 37:05.500\nShut up.\n\n37:05.500 --> 37:09.500\nSo how many drafts of this?\n\n37:09.500 --> 37:13.500\nI mean, you wrote it, you unspec,\n\n37:13.500 --> 37:16.500\ndid you do multiple drafts before you started handing it around?\n\n37:16.500 --> 37:21.500\nDid you start doing multiple drafts when John Davidson and Paul Verhoeven got involved?\n\n37:21.500 --> 37:25.500\nI have a partner on this, so let me get to that.\n\n37:25.500 --> 37:31.500\nSo the way it worked was I was sort of a semi-miserable junior executive at Universal,\n\n37:31.500 --> 37:34.500\nand I was trying to meet people that were interesting to me.\n\n37:34.500 --> 37:39.500\nSo I actually put the word out to UCLA film schools, particularly because I'd been there,\n\n37:39.500 --> 37:42.500\nthat anybody who wanted to come in and talk to me could.\n\n37:42.500 --> 37:46.500\nAnd so all these people who didn't pay any attention to me before came to see me,\n\n37:46.500 --> 37:50.500\namong the Michael Miner, who was seven years older than I was,\n\n37:50.500 --> 37:53.500\nand he was kind of a star at UCLA.\n\n37:53.500 --> 37:56.500\nHe made a movie and he had been a DP,\n\n37:56.500 --> 37:59.500\nand he said, what do you want to do?\n\n37:59.500 --> 38:02.500\nWell, I'm working on this movie about a robot, and I told him,\n\n38:02.500 --> 38:05.500\nit's called Robocop, and it's about a robot, and I told him the story,\n\n38:05.500 --> 38:07.500\nand he was like, oh, let's do that.\n\n38:07.500 --> 38:09.500\nAnd I didn't really have anything much better on.\n\n38:09.500 --> 38:11.500\nI had slowed down a little bit with it.\n\n38:11.500 --> 38:13.500\nIt was taking me about a year since I had done it.\n\n38:13.500 --> 38:17.500\nSo I said, OK, why don't we write a script together?\n\n38:17.500 --> 38:23.500\nAnd I had it fairly well outlined the first act, as it is now, more or less.\n\n38:23.500 --> 38:27.500\nAnd the ending was there, and the middle was a little bit more of a mess.\n\n38:27.500 --> 38:32.500\nAnd the first thing I did was I kind of wanted to write the first act on my own.\n\n38:32.500 --> 38:34.500\nI didn't want to hurt Michael's feelings, but I didn't know him that well yet,\n\n38:34.500 --> 38:36.500\nand I wanted to make sure I was getting it.\n\n38:36.500 --> 38:43.500\nAnd so I told my bosses at Universal that my grandfather had died.\n\n38:43.500 --> 38:45.500\nHe had died a long time ago.\n\n38:45.500 --> 38:46.500\nSo it wasn't a lie.\n\n38:46.500 --> 38:47.500\nHe died in World War II.\n\n38:47.500 --> 38:50.500\nI had to go, and I went back to San Enselmo where I grew up,\n\n38:50.500 --> 38:53.500\nand a friend had left me their house to work on,\n\n38:53.500 --> 38:57.500\nand I wrote the first act in about two weeks.\n\n38:57.500 --> 39:01.500\nAnd during that time, they sent me flowers, which I felt really bad about.\n\n39:01.500 --> 39:05.500\nAnd when I came back, I had to go back to work, and I stopped working.\n\n39:05.500 --> 39:07.500\nAnd then we kind of finished it on nights and weekends,\n\n39:07.500 --> 39:09.500\nbut the first act sort of set the tone.\n\n39:09.500 --> 39:14.500\nAnd then we had a really rough draft, and we gave it to some friends.\n\n39:14.500 --> 39:17.500\nAnd I gave it to, I had made friends who knew a guy named John Davison,\n\n39:17.500 --> 39:20.500\nwho had done Airplane, and I had heard about him.\n\n39:20.500 --> 39:23.500\nJohn Davison was a particular character, had a particular way of speaking,\n\n39:23.500 --> 39:25.500\nand everybody would imitate the way he talked.\n\n39:25.500 --> 39:28.500\nAnd I could even kind of talk like him before I met him.\n\n39:28.500 --> 39:32.500\nBut when I had the script, I gave it to a friend of his,\n\n39:32.500 --> 39:36.500\na director named Jonathan Kaplan, that a friend of a friend knew,\n\n39:36.500 --> 39:38.500\nhoping that he would give it to John Davison.\n\n39:38.500 --> 39:40.500\nAnd he did give it to John Davison.\n\n39:40.500 --> 39:42.500\nHe said John Davison would be perfect for this.\n\n39:42.500 --> 39:45.500\nAnd it was sort of amazing because John Davison was perfect for it,\n\n39:45.500 --> 39:46.500\nfor a whole bunch of reasons.\n\n39:46.500 --> 39:48.500\nWait, wait, he did Airplane.\n\n39:48.500 --> 39:49.500\nHe did Airplane?\n\n39:49.500 --> 39:51.500\nThat seems like a weird fit.\n\n39:51.500 --> 39:53.500\nWell, except it was funny.\n\n39:53.500 --> 39:55.500\nAnd I wanted this to be funny.\n\n39:55.500 --> 39:56.500\nSo I think that was helpful.\n\n39:56.500 --> 39:58.500\nOther people read it, and they thought it was serious,\n\n39:58.500 --> 39:59.500\nand they thought it should be serious.\n\n39:59.500 --> 40:00.500\nHe was the only one who said,\n\n40:00.500 --> 40:02.500\nah, this could be funny, you know?\n\n40:02.500 --> 40:04.500\nAnd he had the cash, he had proven that...\n\n40:04.500 --> 40:06.500\nWell, he had a deal with Orion.\n\n40:06.500 --> 40:09.500\nHe was a really, he is a very, a penurious producer.\n\n40:09.500 --> 40:11.500\nHe makes everything as cheap as he can.\n\n40:11.500 --> 40:12.500\nPenurious.\n\n40:12.500 --> 40:13.500\nPenurious.\n\n40:13.500 --> 40:15.500\nThat's a new word for me.\n\n40:15.500 --> 40:17.500\nNot a new word for any of those languages.\n\n40:17.500 --> 40:20.500\nI just the first time I've ever heard that word.\n\n40:20.500 --> 40:21.500\nHe's not just a writer.\n\n40:21.500 --> 40:23.500\nHe makes up words all the time.\n\n40:23.500 --> 40:27.500\nAt what point did the prime directives like start coming in?\n\n40:27.500 --> 40:32.500\nBecause I want to talk about the ending at one point, because...\n\n40:32.500 --> 40:33.500\nWell, how about later?\n\n40:33.500 --> 40:35.500\nIt's an ending.\n\n40:35.500 --> 40:36.500\nThat's why he says later.\n\n40:36.500 --> 40:38.500\nHere's what, I'll pitch you what I want to talk about.\n\n40:38.500 --> 40:40.500\nYou can tell us who's a better...\n\n40:42.500 --> 40:46.500\nWell, I'm so curious about now the Verhoeven entering this picture,\n\n40:46.500 --> 40:49.500\nbecause I'm picturing the producers and it's springtime for Hitler.\n\n40:49.500 --> 40:54.500\nVerhoeven character enters the story.\n\n40:54.500 --> 40:56.500\nLet me fast forward to this.\n\n40:56.500 --> 40:58.500\nWe get set up.\n\n40:58.500 --> 41:04.500\nWe get a deal at Orion, which is a big deal for people who have never done anything before.\n\n41:04.500 --> 41:08.500\nWe go over there and they give us some notes.\n\n41:08.500 --> 41:14.500\nOne of the notes was somehow the bad guy Clarence and the guy at the top, Dick Jones,\n\n41:14.500 --> 41:16.500\nshould be somehow joined.\n\n41:16.500 --> 41:18.500\nThat was the only real work we took from them.\n\n41:18.500 --> 41:19.500\nThat's a good note.\n\n41:19.500 --> 41:20.500\nIt was a good note.\n\n41:20.500 --> 41:22.500\nAnd so we wrote a second draft.\n\n41:22.500 --> 41:26.500\nAnd midway through the draft, I turned to Michael and I said,\n\n41:26.500 --> 41:28.500\nMichael, this can be funny.\n\n41:28.500 --> 41:30.500\nIt's okay if it's funny.\n\n41:30.500 --> 41:33.500\nAnd we started having fun writing a script.\n\n41:33.500 --> 41:36.500\nNow, that has never happened to me since and hadn't happened to me before.\n\n41:36.500 --> 41:39.500\nBut it was fun for about two weeks.\n\n41:39.500 --> 41:43.500\nAnd we laughed and we made jokes and we couldn't believe how entertaining we were.\n\n41:43.500 --> 41:45.500\nAnd we wrote it pretty well.\n\n41:45.500 --> 41:50.500\nIs that where the absurd elements, I'd buy that for a dollar, runner, or is that?\n\n41:50.500 --> 41:54.500\nI'd have to look and see.\n\n41:54.500 --> 41:56.500\nI'd buy that for a dollar.\n\n41:56.500 --> 42:00.500\nI had spent some time at Paramount around all the Gary Marshall sitcoms.\n\n42:00.500 --> 42:04.500\nSo that was my attempt at coming up with a tagline for a...\n\n42:04.500 --> 42:08.500\nBy the way, when your system is shocked, and we all know this from writing a roller coaster,\n\n42:08.500 --> 42:14.500\nI mean, not only are you having this weird, like, why am I laughing? I'm terrified.\n\n42:14.500 --> 42:19.500\nSo we're already familiar with, like, you can get a good laugh out of somebody who's scared shitless\n\n42:19.500 --> 42:21.500\nor upset just like...\n\n42:21.500 --> 42:22.500\nYeah, it's a pressure release.\n\n42:22.500 --> 42:24.500\nTraumatized, absolutely.\n\n42:24.500 --> 42:29.500\nBut it also occurs to me that it works the opposite way, too.\n\n42:29.500 --> 42:35.500\nThe villains in Robocop are especially traumatizing.\n\n42:35.500 --> 42:41.500\nAnd therefore, you're very immersed in Peter Weller's character, Murphy, who becomes Robocop.\n\n42:41.500 --> 42:51.500\nLike, his conduit to becoming Robocop is a horrible, violent trend.\n\n42:51.500 --> 42:57.500\nAnd it's absolutely more horrific because these guys are goofballs.\n\n42:57.500 --> 43:00.500\nThey fancy themselves real cut-ups.\n\n43:00.500 --> 43:11.500\nAnd their leader, played by Kirkwood Smith, is like, I had never seen a receding hairline guy\n\n43:11.500 --> 43:16.500\nwith glasses playing a villain in an action movie.\n\n43:16.500 --> 43:21.500\nThat counted as diversity back then.\n\n43:21.500 --> 43:27.500\nBecause he looked like he should be giving James Bond his weapons in a lab, and he's the big bad.\n\n43:27.500 --> 43:35.500\nHe was so effective, the sway he held over his minions, the way they interacted with each other,\n\n43:35.500 --> 43:41.500\nthe fact that they watched television and enjoyed it, that they went in and out of being grody.\n\n43:41.500 --> 43:43.500\nIt was just, you felt...\n\n43:43.500 --> 43:45.500\nHe taught Bobby how to fly?\n\n43:45.500 --> 43:46.500\nYou felt so...\n\n43:46.500 --> 43:48.500\nWell, that's an example.\n\n43:48.500 --> 43:53.500\nYeah, I mean, he's not gonna slow his adrenaline junkiness down.\n\n43:53.500 --> 43:59.500\nHe's throwing one of his minions, the thing, but it was just like, you're watching Peter Weller go into that warehouse,\n\n43:59.500 --> 44:03.500\nand if you're watching this movie a sixth, seventh, eight hundredth time,\n\n44:03.500 --> 44:15.500\nyou're now realizing that this first act has been so cold riveted tightly that the corporate story has been mentioning offhand.\n\n44:15.500 --> 44:18.500\nYes, we've been relocating candidates according to risk factor,\n\n44:18.500 --> 44:24.500\nand that you're going like, oh, God, and Peter Weller was available...\n\n44:24.500 --> 44:26.500\nMurphy was available for that job.\n\n44:26.500 --> 44:29.500\nHe was a candidate that was relocated according to risk factor.\n\n44:29.500 --> 44:30.500\nWhy?\n\n44:30.500 --> 44:33.500\nBecause his kid loves TJ Laser.\n\n44:33.500 --> 44:34.500\nHe wants to...\n\n44:34.500 --> 44:38.500\nNancy Allen asks him, what are you doing with your gun?\n\n44:38.500 --> 44:42.500\nHe's like, well, I just want to learn this thing.\n\n44:42.500 --> 44:45.500\nSo is that the desire of the character to be a good cop?\n\n44:45.500 --> 44:46.500\nYeah.\n\n44:46.500 --> 44:47.500\nI think it is, actually.\n\n44:47.500 --> 44:48.500\nTo be a cowboy.\n\n44:48.500 --> 44:52.500\nI was looking at your story cycle, and I thought, oh, the scene where he says,\n\n44:52.500 --> 44:56.500\nmy kid wants me to be a good cop, and all good cops do that.\n\n44:56.500 --> 44:57.500\nHe has...\n\n44:57.500 --> 45:02.500\nWe're going to find out through ghostly flashbacks as this character that we become is trapped in this metal cage,\n\n45:02.500 --> 45:06.500\nbut we'll find out that he actually had an idyllic life.\n\n45:06.500 --> 45:11.500\nWe can only speculate that it wasn't enough for him for what reason.\n\n45:11.500 --> 45:17.500\nGod, the best reason of all, not because he was tired of fucking his beautiful wife, not because he wished he had more money,\n\n45:17.500 --> 45:21.500\nbecause he felt like maybe he was failing as a dad.\n\n45:21.500 --> 45:25.500\nAnd I would say the subtext there was like, you're seeing the flashbacks.\n\n45:25.500 --> 45:26.500\nThe kid is watching television.\n\n45:26.500 --> 45:28.500\nHe's watching TJ Laser.\n\n45:28.500 --> 45:33.500\nThese days, what that would be is the kid was so absorbed in his iPad,\n\n45:33.500 --> 45:39.500\nor he was literally jacked into some video game, and it was like, how can I reach this kid?\n\n45:39.500 --> 45:43.500\nI want to become a bigger-than-life thing.\n\n45:43.500 --> 45:48.500\nI want this kid to understand that law enforcement can be heroic,\n\n45:48.500 --> 45:53.500\nwhich is absolutely the opposite realization that this world is going through.\n\n45:53.500 --> 46:00.500\nThey're having their first police strike following the purchase of the police at the hands of a consumer electronics company.\n\n46:00.500 --> 46:03.500\nAnd so the cops are having this...\n\n46:03.500 --> 46:05.500\nThere's just so many goddamn details.\n\n46:05.500 --> 46:07.500\nI just went off on this weird off-road thing.\n\n46:07.500 --> 46:10.500\nBut yeah, I mean, I do. It's funny that you're asking.\n\n46:10.500 --> 46:16.500\nAnd that's another thing that I think is so amazing about the job is that you can ask questions like that,\n\n46:16.500 --> 46:22.500\neven though you wrote the goddamn script, because how much of the...\n\n46:22.500 --> 46:24.500\nThis job is about channeling, isn't it?\n\n46:24.500 --> 46:28.500\nIt's not clear how much you can know and how much just comes in somehow.\n\n46:28.500 --> 46:31.500\nIt's really amazing when it happens, and it's not reliable.\n\n46:31.500 --> 46:36.500\nI truly believe that these things are out there, and that when we're doing our best,\n\n46:36.500 --> 46:39.500\nwe're doing the opposite of proving that we're good at what we do.\n\n46:39.500 --> 46:48.500\nWe're actually only able to untighten some sphincter in us just enough to accidentally let something noble.\n\n46:48.500 --> 46:51.500\nThat just needs an antenna.\n\n46:51.500 --> 46:53.500\nI don't know if we were trying to do anything noble,\n\n46:53.500 --> 46:58.500\nbut it was like just pursuing the things you were interested in and really saying,\n\n46:58.500 --> 47:00.500\nwell, there were all sorts of things that...\n\n47:00.500 --> 47:07.500\nLike, Ed 209, when I sat down with Phil Tippett, we started looking at certain kind of Japanese things,\n\n47:07.500 --> 47:12.500\nand then I said, yeah, but what this is really about, Phil, is it's really like, it's kind of the Vietnam War.\n\n47:12.500 --> 47:17.500\nThis is a Huey helicopter, and this guy, Dr. McNamara, is there, and it's...\n\n47:17.500 --> 47:20.500\nI didn't push that there, but I was always in the background there,\n\n47:20.500 --> 47:23.500\nand then when you look at it, you realize, oh, that is kind of like a helicopter.\n\n47:23.500 --> 47:24.500\nThat is kind of like that.\n\n47:24.500 --> 47:27.500\nAnd with Rabotin, who did the suit, we talked...\n\n47:27.500 --> 47:28.500\nSo fucking cool.\n\n47:28.500 --> 47:30.500\nAnd Rabotin is a great artist.\n\n47:30.500 --> 47:31.500\nSo fucking cool.\n\n47:31.500 --> 47:32.500\nI mean, these are...\n\n47:32.500 --> 47:35.500\nHe had him, Phil Tippett, I mean, Jesus.\n\n47:35.500 --> 47:38.500\nAnd he said, and one day, many years later, I said, you know,\n\n47:38.500 --> 47:40.500\nit's really interesting because it's all about Detroit.\n\n47:40.500 --> 47:41.500\nAnd what I...\n\n47:41.500 --> 47:46.500\nThe book I had read kind of as research for this was a book called The Reckoning by David Halberstam,\n\n47:46.500 --> 47:51.500\nall about how Detroit and Nissan had gone to war and Detroit had lost.\n\n47:51.500 --> 47:54.500\nAnd it was about the decline of the American car.\n\n47:54.500 --> 47:57.500\nAnd that was like what I was writing about with the decline of corporate stuff.\n\n47:57.500 --> 47:59.500\nI was a kid who liked cars.\n\n47:59.500 --> 48:01.500\nAnd this was the meaning of it.\n\n48:01.500 --> 48:02.500\nAnd when you look at...\n\n48:02.500 --> 48:07.500\nOne day I said to Rabotin, I said, it really looks like a truck, man.\n\n48:07.500 --> 48:09.500\nIt looks like a ram truck or something like it.\n\n48:09.500 --> 48:10.500\nIt looks like American road iron.\n\n48:10.500 --> 48:12.500\nAnd Rabotin was like, oh, I like that.\n\n48:12.500 --> 48:13.500\nBut I think it really did.\n\n48:13.500 --> 48:16.500\nI think he channeled that because it looks like a car in a weird way.\n\n48:16.500 --> 48:17.500\nWhen you look at the design...\n\n48:17.500 --> 48:19.500\nAnd they end up at an abandoned steel mill.\n\n48:19.500 --> 48:21.500\nI mean, it's where he has to go.\n\n48:21.500 --> 48:24.500\nIt's where metal is made and unmade.\n\n48:24.500 --> 48:27.500\nNo, it's all about the rust belt. And that's why it was Detroit.\n\n48:27.500 --> 48:29.500\nAnd that's why it was this kind of thing.\n\n48:29.500 --> 48:31.500\nAnd I remember the line producer saying, well, come on.\n\n48:31.500 --> 48:32.500\nWe can shoot it.\n\n48:32.500 --> 48:34.500\nAnd Los Angeles can go home at night.\n\n48:34.500 --> 48:38.500\nBut somehow going to Pittsburgh to this horrible little...\n\n48:38.500 --> 48:41.500\nThis awful place where the town had fallen apart\n\n48:41.500 --> 48:44.500\naround this old steel mill that was haunted.\n\n48:44.500 --> 48:45.500\nAnd backstage...\n\n48:45.500 --> 48:46.500\nFun fact, we established that.\n\n48:46.500 --> 48:48.500\nIt's Ed 209 and his name is also Ed.\n\n48:48.500 --> 48:49.500\nSo he threw that one in there.\n\n48:49.500 --> 48:51.500\nI love that.\n\n48:51.500 --> 48:56.500\nIf I could show you a tally of the number of times in 20 years\n\n48:56.500 --> 48:59.500\nthat in the most important of conversations that I've had,\n\n48:59.500 --> 49:02.500\nand it's important to me relative to what I was working on,\n\n49:02.500 --> 49:05.500\nhow important it was for me to try to communicate something,\n\n49:05.500 --> 49:10.500\nthe number of times that I have referenced story points in Robocop\n\n49:10.500 --> 49:13.500\nso that I could achieve some kind of vocabulary with whoever I'm talking to,\n\n49:13.500 --> 49:15.500\nwhether or not they'd seen the movie.\n\n49:15.500 --> 49:18.500\nBecause honestly, as long as I know what I'm talking about,\n\n49:18.500 --> 49:21.500\nthen maybe I have a chance of explaining to this other person.\n\n49:21.500 --> 49:27.500\nOtherwise, I'm just babbling this like paste of fucking like...\n\n49:27.500 --> 49:29.500\nNon-connected references.\n\n49:29.500 --> 49:34.500\nBut for me to be able to dive into a story that is so well constructed\n\n49:34.500 --> 49:38.500\nthat I can also then later when I'm talking to the same person go,\n\n49:38.500 --> 49:40.500\nremember that thing I keep referencing Robocop?\n\n49:40.500 --> 49:42.500\nWell, now we're talking about this part of the story.\n\n49:42.500 --> 49:44.500\nSo again, I'm going to reference that.\n\n49:44.500 --> 49:46.500\nNow you already know what I explain to you.\n\n49:46.500 --> 49:53.500\nEvery threshold, the atonement with the father being so literal,\n\n49:53.500 --> 49:57.500\nit's amazing that that was a note that a suit gave that was like,\n\n49:57.500 --> 49:59.500\neh, and it's such a...\n\n49:59.500 --> 50:02.500\nFrom the mouths of babes or capitalists,\n\n50:02.500 --> 50:06.500\nit's just sort of like, I'd like to see both bad guys be cousins.\n\n50:06.500 --> 50:09.500\nIt's kind of a shrug like, yeah, it'd be easier to follow about.\n\n50:09.500 --> 50:11.500\nBut it's like, I had heard like,\n\n50:11.500 --> 50:16.500\nBrillstein or Gray or somebody like when Bob and David pitched Mr. Show,\n\n50:16.500 --> 50:19.500\nthey were like, it should be Mr. Show with Bob and David.\n\n50:19.500 --> 50:21.500\nOtherwise, people like people.\n\n50:21.500 --> 50:26.500\nBut it was sort of like, you guys should come out and introduce the show.\n\n50:26.500 --> 50:29.500\nAnd then at the time, I think they thought that was such a ridiculous\n\n50:29.500 --> 50:31.500\nlike baby boomerang note.\n\n50:31.500 --> 50:36.500\nBut I mean, it's like, god damn, what a great note.\n\n50:36.500 --> 50:43.500\nBut you could take a stopwatch\n\n50:43.500 --> 50:49.500\nand you could take a circle and break the 360 degrees down\n\n50:49.500 --> 50:52.500\nso that every second meant how many pages or whatever.\n\n50:52.500 --> 50:55.500\nAnd you could go around that movie\n\n50:55.500 --> 51:01.500\nand kaboom the moment when Joseph Campbell, who has never met you\n\n51:01.500 --> 51:07.500\nand who didn't even like movies, is talking about the importance\n\n51:07.500 --> 51:11.500\nof this sort of like going to meet your maker\n\n51:11.500 --> 51:18.500\nand how the extent to which you are still driven by 